AUDIO: 'Plants can count. Plants can talk. Plants can communicate complex ideas through a variety of forms and so can bacteria and nematodes. What is intelligence? If you do not know the answer to that question or what\'s required to create intelligence, you\'re in very good company because researchers'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are trying to figure that out. We will talk about it. We have already known that at least some plants can count. I mean, Venus flytraps will wait to be touched at least five times before they clamp down on a fly, but they\'ve also found other plants like the mimosa. Yes,'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the shy plant, the one that wilts when you touch it. That one knows the number of days. You can leave them in the light for a couple of days and then in the dark for three and they\'ll learn to anticipate light. This actually builds on some other research that people weren\'t entirely'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sure if they could replicate and that was to do with operant conditioning and classical conditioning in plants. Yes, we have more evidence for it because that is how science operates. We\'ve seen plants do things like communicate pretty complex information with each other,'

