VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'organization of our neurons works. That is why we use it, but we are not the only critters that use it. Other critters like plants have decided entirely other mechanisms to communicate with and C. elegans figured out vomiting'

[02:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'memories which are edible. I suppose it\'s real good news and maybe this is just me, but tardigrades are making a comeback this time in neuroscience. Tardigrades are ridiculously smart for what they are. They\'re microscopic. They'

[02:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have this little thing on the front of their face that they used to pierce open cells like bacteria or plant cells and suck out the goo, sometimes out of each other. But, they have to process vision, they have to operate complex bodies and they don\'t have a brain in the same way'

[03:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we do. They have a central ganglion, kind of like a primitive brain. This makes them a wonderful way to study the development of animal neuroscience. And they\'re really hardy in a lab. They\'re easy to grow and you can do just about'

[03:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'anything and they will survive making them in many ways an ideal model organism. We are, now mind you, finding complex behavior in things like plants and bacteria. I am quite sure we\'re going to find complex behavior in tardigrades.'

